A First Pass at Empirical Frequency

Now that weâ€™ve defined our goal clearly, it should be easy to provide a quantitative answer â€“ all weâ€™ve got to do is find a suitable dataset!

With this in mind, I fired up my xpath skills and navigated on over to the website of Chinaâ€™s official state media organization, Xinhua=æ–°åŽ. Even if you donâ€™t understand a white of Chinese, knowing that itâ€™s a news website, the basic structure should be clear. The dayâ€™s top headlines (at least according to Xinhuaâ€™s editors) are presented with pictures and links to articles.

I decided to pull all the characters from all links (<a> nodes) on the top page, then follow all of the internal links on the first page and pull the characters from the linked pages as well. Some links/photo captions/paragraphs are intentionally duplicated, so subsequent instances of identical blocks were eliminated. Full code is available on the projectâ€™s GitHub repo; hereâ€™s the core snippet that extracts and counts the characters from an article:

article_counts = read_html_or_sleep(article) %>% 
  html_nodes(xpath = '//p|//div[@class="h-title"]') %>% 
  blocks_to_zi %>% zi_counts

article is a URL string; blocks_to_zi takes nodes, converts them to text, strips non-Chinese characters, eliminates duplicates, then converts strings to individual characters; zi_counts takes a vector of characters and converts them to a data.table of unique characters and their frequency in the vector.

Doing so created a dataset of roughly 200,000 appearances of 2,909 distinct characters. What are the most common?

This plot shows the top 500 characters on Xinhua. Relative frequency is encoded by the background shading of each cell. That there is so little apparent variation in the shade outside the top row owes to the extreme relative concentration in those top rows â€“ the top character (çš„) represents fully 2.6% of all characters and is roughly 4.5 times more common than even the 10th most frequent, and 13.4 times more common than the 100th. The color gradient is much more gradual on the log scale:

Another way of visualizing this concentration is to depict the CDF of the distribution of characters (ordering the discretization starting from the most common character). This allows us to judge at a glance percentiles:

The slope of this curve at zero is quite sharp, which is just another way of thinking about the concentration that we observed above. We can also see that, despite an intimidating total count of characters, the number of characters required to get a general gist of an article (defined as being able to understand half of its characters) is only 180! This is non-trivial (definitely wonâ€™t be done in a day, a week, or even a month if youâ€™re studying part-time), but the Himalayan mountain of 100,000 characters has been reduced to a manageable Appalachian foothill (or, how about Bukit Timah Hill for local context, though even that is still an order of magnitude too relatively large). 464 characters only appeared once in my sample; fully 38% appear at most 5 times.

So, there we go, right? We can now focus our efforts on mastering the characters in this chart and get back to learning grammar, vocabulary, practicing speech, etc.

Except â€“ not so fast. What this chart tells us is that knowing these 500 characters will enable us to understand 1% of characters in Xinhua articles, from the day on which I sampled these articles back in November.
